's imperial periphery by "russifying" the land and marginalizing the Indigenous Kazakh population. In the first study exploring the role of Orthodoxy in settler colonialism, Aileen Friesen shows how settlers, clergymen, and state officials viewed the recreation of Orthodox parish life as practised in European Russia as fundamental to the establishment of settler communities, and to the success of colonization. Friesen uniquely gives peasant settlers a voice in this discussion, as they expressed their religious aspirations and fears to priests and tsarist officials. Despite this agreement, tensions existed not only among settlers, but also within the Orthodox Church as these groups struggled to define what constituted the Russian Orthodox faith and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch and statexHistoryy19th centuryzKazakhstan. 0aChurch and statexHistoryy19th centuryzRussia (Federation)zSiberia. 0aChurch and statezKazakhstanxHistoryy19th century. 0aChurch and statezRussia (Federation)zSiberiaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781487534554zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487534554zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487534554/original  a978-3-11-069045-3 University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127253-5 ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA